body:
The compiler given a hint about where the error is and can be corrected but this hint is confusing.

I created a minimal reproducer:

https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=stable&mode=debug&edition=2018&gist=a96e7ba43b8b5661ab523c518653f026

```rust
pub struct A;
pub struct B;

impl From<u32> for A {
    fn from(_v: u32) -> Self {
        todo!()
    }
}

impl From<u32> for B {
    fn from(_v: u32) -> Self {
        todo!()
    }
}

impl From<B> for A {
    fn from(_v: B) -> Self {
        todo!()
    }
}

fn main() {
    let a1: A = A::from(0u32);
    A::from(0u32.into());
}
```

I expected to see this happen:

An error about line 24 type annotations needed or the code to compile (A is well defined and there is no ambiguity about which from to use).

Instead, this happened:

```
error[E0283]: type annotations needed for `A`
  --> src/main.rs:24:5
   |
23 |     let a1: A = A::from(0u32);
   |         -- consider giving `a1` a type
24 |     A::from(0u32.into());
   |     ^^^^^^^ cannot infer type for struct `A`
   |
   = note: cannot resolve `A: std::convert::From<_>`
   = note: required by `std::convert::From::from`
```

A hint to consider giving a1 a type, which makes no sense as these lines aren't related.
